    	<h2><a name="2003-08-09" href="#2003-08-09"><font color="#660000">2003-08-09</font></a></h2>
   	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046593112577763">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h1>Digital Security</h1><br /><a href="http://java.sun.com/docs/books/tutorial/security1.2/index.html">Security in Java 2 SDK 1.2</a>.&nbsp; Good heavens, I know the author of this trail!<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046593112577763">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046519924985703">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.trusted-time.com/time_stamping_products.asp">Trusted Time - Authentication and Encryption</a>.&nbsp; An important aspect of digital signatures is having authentic time stamps that confirm when a signature was made and that makes for a non-repudiatable indication of when and whom.&nbsp; This is something that is to be checked out further in the context of XML Digital Signatures and other schemes for establishing provenance and chains of custody.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046519924985703">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046501153808247">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.tokenguard.com/tg_default.asp?currency=">computer security, laptop security, pc security, security kits using award-winning usb etoken</a>.&nbsp; This is an interesting system.  The one-year Class 2 Personal Certificates go for $47.01 and the kit (including a certificate) goes for $93.32 in the US.  This depends on the TokenTrust and it looks like something that it would be interesting to dig into, especially the automatic log-on for Windows XP using the token!<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046501153808247">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046435802319550">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://csrc.ncsl.nist.gov/CryptoToolkit/CryptoToolkit.html">Cryptographic Toolkit - Index</a>.&nbsp; This is the unframed page that I was able to blog.&nbsp; To get the full framed depiction, go to the <a href="http://csrc.ncsl.nist.gov/CryptoToolkit/">CryptoToolkit</a> section.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046435802319550">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046414560982763">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://csrc.ncsl.nist.gov/cryptval/cmvp.htm">Cryptographic Module Validation Program</a>.&nbsp; This is information on the NIST program, with links to the various sources, requirements, and so on.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046414560982763">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046362415011297">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h2>Digital Signature Standards</h2><a href="http://csrc.ncsl.nist.gov/cryptval/dss.htm">DSA, RSA, ECDSA (FIPS 186-2); SHA-1 (FIPS 180-1)</a>.&nbsp; A summary of the 3 Digital Signature Algorithms (DSA, RSA, and ECDSA) that are accepted under the FIPS Digital Signature Standard as of February 15, 2000.&nbsp; There are useful resources, including sources of all referenced specifications and standards.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046362415011297">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046250175565350">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.abanet.org/scitech/ec/isc/dsg-tutorial.html">Digital Signature Guidelines - Tutorial</a>.&nbsp; This is a nicely done, comprehensive tutorial that addresses the historical, social, and legal aspects of signatures and the challenges and opportunities for providing those facilities in digital transactions.  "Open systems, by retaining a high degree of information security, even for information sent over open, insecure, but inexpensive and widely used channels. ".&nbsp; A key point with regard to the appeal and the opportunity.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046250175565350">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046230265514364">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.articsoft.com/pki.htm">An Introduction to Public Key Infrastructure</a>.&nbsp; This is a nice introduction ", covering pki, public key cryptography, public key, private key, public key infrastructure, x.509 certificates, encryption, digital signatures, certificate revocation, certificate authorities."<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046230265514364">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046201169498273">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.itl.nist.gov/fipspubs/fip186.htm">FIPS 186 - (DSS), Digital Signature Standard</a>.&nbsp; This 1994 specification includes the Digital Signature Algorithm (DSA) that is also refered to in the XML Digital Signature specification and used in examples.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046201169498273">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046185343795566">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.digsigtrust.com/federal/dod.html">Federal Government > Dept. of Defense IECA PKI</a>.&nbsp; The US DoD will require use of PKI certificates and signatures for access to DoD systems, starting in October 2003.  Obtaining one from the Digital Signature Trust costs USD $119 for an individual certificate (good for one year).&nbsp; That is an X.509 certificate, the most-common one promoted by certificate authorities.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046185343795566">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046140571112454">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://rechten.kub.nl/simone/ds-lawsu.htm">Digital Signature Law Survey</a>.&nbsp; Simone van der Hof's survey site that provides information on laws involving the introduction/allowance/requirement of digital signatures.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046140571112454">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106046126653267826">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.youdzone.com/signature.html">What is a Digital Signature?</a>.&nbsp; An introduction to Digital Signatures, by David Youd.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106046126653267826">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106045901162769266">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h1>Web Services</h1><h2>Service-Oriented Architectures and Component Frameworks</h2><br /><a href="http://www.computerworld.com/printthis/2003/0,4814,83410,00.html">Code Reuse Gets Easier - Computerworld</a>.&nbsp; A column on what it takes to achieve reusability.&nbsp; This is worthwhile in terms of exploration of Web Services and also looking at what it takes at the development level to create and use component frameworks.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106045901162769266">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106045092478647565">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<h3>Web Services Security</h3><a href="http://www.jcp.org/en/jsr/detail?id=106">The Java Community Process(SM) JSR 106 - XML Digital Encryption APIs</a>.&nbsp; This process, being led by an expert from IBM, is not so advanced as the work on XML Digital Signatures, although the group was created in March, 2001.  Until some sort of public review stage is reached, there is no visibility on this activity.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106045092478647565">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106045067700806385">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://www.jcp.org/en/jsr/detail?id=105">The Java Community Process(SM) JSR 105 - XML Digital Signature APIs</a>.&nbsp; This provides information on APIs for accomplishing XML Digital Signatures.&nbsp; This specification has completed public review and can be downloaded here.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106045067700806385">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	

	<div class="posts">
	<a name="106045027210424725">&nbsp;</a><br>
	<a href="http://researchweb.watson.ibm.com/journal/sj/412/hondo.html">Securing Web services</a>.&nbsp; A nice find based on a link from classmate Fernando.  A comprehensive discussion of the considerations and the many ways to rely on XML Digital Signature and XML Encryption as support.  The 3d party issue is not addressed fully, and there is no discussion of proxy issues in trust chains.  And this is a very nice compilation and explanation.<br>
	<span class="byline">posted by Dennis at <a href="#106045027210424725">Saturday, August 09, 2003</a></span></div>
<br>
  <!-- 2002-11-08 Change date format to yyyy-mm-dd and bookmark it 
                2002-11-09 Tune the color and make a purplized link out of it -->
	
